Wastewater as a Sentinel for Emerging Antimicrobial Resistance Threats: A Review

Timoth Mkilima, 
First published: 08 July 2025
https://doi.org/10.1002/tqem.70115
Sections
PDF
Tools

ABSTRACT

Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) represents a global health crisis, threatening to render many of our most effective antibiotics obsolete. Traditional surveillance methods, which focus on symptomatic patients, provide a reactive and limited view of resistance trends, often overlooking the early indicators of emerging AMR threats. This review advocates for a paradigm shift in AMR surveillance, emphasizing the potential of wastewater-based epidemiology (WBE) as a proactive, real-time monitoring tool. By harnessing advanced molecular techniques, WBE offers an unprecedented opportunity to track antimicrobial resistance genes (AMRGs) in populations, even in areas with limited healthcare infrastructure. Rather than merely counting pathogens, WBE allows for the detection of subtle shifts in the resistome, providing a clearer picture of resistance dynamics before they reach clinical settings. This approach not only offers early warnings of potential resistance outbreaks but also enables global surveillance, contributing to a more comprehensive understanding of AMR trends and the effectiveness of mitigation strategies. Ultimately, wastewater surveillance is poised to become a cornerstone in the fight against AMR, offering a forward-looking approach to safeguarding the efficacy of antibiotics for future generations.

1 Introduction

Antimicrobial resistance (AMR) presents one of the most significant threats to global health, with far-reaching consequences for public health, medical treatments, and economic stability. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), AMR is responsible for an estimated 700,000 deaths annually worldwide, with projections suggesting that this figure could increase to 10 million deaths by 2050 if left unaddressed (Talaat et al. 2022). The potential economic cost of AMR is similarly alarming, with global losses estimated to reach $100 trillion by mid-century (Ahmed et al. 2024). This threat is compounded by the gradual erosion of the effectiveness of antimicrobial drugs, which has led to the rise of so-called superbugs that are resistant to multiple classes of antibiotics. The need for more effective and timely surveillance of AMR is critical to prevent the escalation of resistance and the loss of therapeutic options (Salam, Al-Amin, Salam et al. 2023).

Traditional AMR surveillance systems, which largely depend on data from clinical settings, offer a reactive approach, often detecting resistance only after it has reached alarming levels. In a 7-year retrospective study conducted at the Mohammed V Military Hospital of Instruction in Morocco, it was found that 12% of Escherichia coli isolates from both inpatient and outpatient urine specimens exhibited resistance to third-generation cephalosporins, a key class of antibiotics commonly prescribed for urinary tract infections (Benaissa et al. 2021). The study also highlighted the significant rise in the extended-spectrum beta-lactamase (ESBL) phenotype, which increased from 3% in 2012 to 11.16% in 2018, further illustrating the growing concern over resistance to critical antibiotics. However, many individuals who carry resistant bacteria may never seek medical attention, meaning that a significant portion of resistance in the population goes undetected. One study estimated that approximately 50% of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) carriers in the general population are asymptomatic and not included in clinical surveillance (Shorr 2007). As a result, current surveillance methods often fail to capture the full scope of AMR in the population, delaying interventions until clinical cases have escalated.

In contrast, wastewater-based epidemiology (WBE) offers a more comprehensive and proactive method for monitoring AMR (Dzinamarira et al. 2022). Wastewater, which is representative of the combined biological waste of entire populations, offers the ability to track resistance trends across broad swathes of the community, including individuals who are asymptomatic or have not sought medical care. A key advantage of WBE is its ability to detect antimicrobial resistance genes (AMRGs) in wastewater samples, providing a snapshot of the resistome in real time (Gholipour et al. 2024). A study conducted in Delhi, India, detected the New Delhi metallo-beta-lactamase (NDM-1) gene in gram-negative bacteria collected from the effluent treatment plant of a tuberculosis care hospital. The study found that 71% of the 138 collected organisms carried the blaNDM-1 gene, and 53.6% of them were double-positive for both blaNDM-1 and the Int-1 gene, associated with integrons that promote gene transfer. Furthermore, nearly 28.9% of the organisms were actively producing metallo-beta-lactamase, highlighting the potential environmental spread of this resistance mechanism (Aggarwal et al. 2020). This suggests that WBE can serve as an early-warning system, providing valuable time for public health responses to emerging AMR threats. In a more recent study, Adegoke et al. (2022) analyzed the prevalence of vancomycin-resistant enterococci (VRE) in wastewater treatment plants (WWTPs) and their impact on receiving water bodies. The influents showed VRE counts between 4.3 and 6.7 log10 CFU/100 mL, while effluent counts dropped to 03.4 log10 CFU/100 mL after chlorination. Of the isolates, 73.8% contained the vanA gene, indicating high resistance. The study found that the treated effluent was less contaminated than the river samples, which had higher VRE counts. Resistance was observed in 34%100% of isolates to antibiotics like quinopristin-dalfopristin, streptomycin, and doxycycline, demonstrating the growing environmental threat posed by VRE. This ability to detect resistance before it reaches clinical settings could be critical for more timely and effective interventions.

The integration of next-generation sequencing (NGS) technologies into WBE has further enhanced the ability to detect and monitor AMR. NGS provides the capability for high-throughput, untargeted detection of both known and novel antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs), offering deeper insights into the diversity and evolution of resistant microbial communities (Satam et al. 2023). For example, a study conducted by Guo et al. (2021), using metagenomic analysis to investigate antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs) in untreated wastewater from three different types of hospitals (general, traditional Chinese medicine, and stomatology hospitals), identified 130 bacterial phyla and 2554 genera. The study found significant differences in bacterial community compositions and ARG types across the hospitals, highlighting the need for targeted protection measures and improved treatment of hospital wastewater to prevent the spread of antibiotic-resistant pathogens into the environment. This level of detail allows for the detection of emerging resistance mechanisms that might otherwise go unnoticed. Additionally, NGS has enabled the identification of specific resistance profiles, helping researchers track the movement of resistance determinants between geographical regions (Yang et al. 2017).

This review explores the transformative potential of WBE in the fight against AMR. By providing an efficient, real-time, and comprehensive method for monitoring the spread of AMR across entire populations and environments, WBE overcomes the limitations of traditional clinical surveillance. With the integration of NGS technologies and continued international collaboration, WBE is poised to play a central role in global AMR surveillance, offering a cost-effective and scalable solution to this growing crisis. Through enhanced monitoring, early detection, and rapid intervention, WBE can help slow the progression of AMR, safeguarding the future of public health and ensuring that effective antimicrobial therapies remain available for generations to come.

2 Literature Review Methodology

The literature review undertaken for this study aimed to provide a clear and evidence-based understanding of the current role and potential of WBE in AMR surveillance. To ensure methodological transparency, the following subsections describe how the relevant literature was identified, selected, and analyzed.

2.1 Search Strategy and Sources

The literature search was mainly conducted using three principal academic databases: PubMed, Scopus, and Web of Science. These platforms were selected for their comprehensive coverage of biomedical sciences, environmental monitoring, and epidemiological research. To supplement this, Google Scholar was also utilized to capture regionally focused studies and grey literature not indexed in the primary databases. The search terms combined keywords related to AMR, wastewater, epidemiology, resistance genes, and surveillance. Boolean operators and truncation techniques were applied to refine the scope and maximize the retrieval of relevant literature.

2.2 Inclusion and Exclusion Parameters

Only peer-reviewed studies that investigated AMR surveillance in wastewater using molecular or genomic techniques were included. Preference was given to studies that provided clear descriptions of their analytical methods and sampling designs, particularly those focusing on the quantification or characterization of ARGs in raw or treated sewage. Studies were excluded if they lacked methodological clarity, did not focus on environmental resistome monitoring, or provided purely theoretical or speculative discussions without empirical support. Non-English publications were excluded to ensure consistency in interpretation, given the technical specificity of the subject matter.

2.3 Study Selection and Screening

All titles and abstracts identified through the search were initially screened to assess basic relevance to WBE and AMR. Full texts of potentially relevant articles were retrieved and further evaluated to determine alignment with the review's focus. Emphasis was placed on studies employing advanced molecular techniques such as qPCR, high-throughput sequencing, or metagenomic analysis, as these reflect current best practices in the field. Articles that relied solely on culture-based pathogen detection or lacked resistome-level analysis were not prioritized unless they contributed significantly to contextual understanding or historical development of the field.

2.4 Geographical and Temporal Scope

The review incorporated studies conducted in various geographical settings to capture the broader application of WBE in AMR surveillance. Most of the accessible and methodologically robust studies originated from contexts with established wastewater treatment infrastructure and routine access to molecular laboratory capabilities. In contrast, fewer studies were identified from areas where such infrastructure and technical capacity remain limited. This disparity influenced the depth and consistency of available data across regions.

2.5 Data Analysis and Synthesis Approach

The data extracted from the selected studies included descriptions of sampling protocols, types of wastewater analyzed, target ARGs, detection methods, and key findings. Rather than applying quantitative meta-analysis; which was not feasible due to methodological heterogeneity; this review adopted a qualitative synthesis approach. Themes were identified across studies regarding detection sensitivity, geographical patterns of ARG prevalence, and the integration of WBE into broader AMR monitoring frameworks. This synthesis was grounded in the actual findings of the reviewed literature, avoiding extrapolation beyond the evidence presented in the original studies.

3 Wastewater as a Molecular Mirror of Community Health

Wastewater is a molecular mirror reflecting the health and activity of entire communities, capturing a comprehensive biological archive that extends far beyond clinical diagnostics. This liquid biopsy encompasses the resistome; the complete set of antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs); including not only those associated with clinically relevant pathogens but also ARGs harbored by commensal bacteria and environmental microbes. The growing concern about untreated wastewater, particularly in developing and low-income countries, highlights the challenges posed by inadequate infrastructure and resources. Only 8%28% of wastewater in these regions undergoes treatment, leaving the majority to be discharged directly into the environment (Amin et al. 2024). This creates a significant pathway for the spread of antibiotic-resistant genes (ARGs) and bacteria (ARB). Such gaps in wastewater management necessitate cost-effective and scalable solutions. A study by Hazra et al. (2022), demonstrated that constructed wetlands (CWs) provide a viable, low-cost approach for addressing this issue. CWs, when integrated with conventional systems, enhance the removal of ARGs and ARB, improving environmental and public health outcomes.

While surveillance of ARGs in wastewater has improved, inconsistencies in methods and scope across studies make global comparisons difficult. This is evident in a review by Tiwari et al. (2022), which analyzed 2235 articles. After de-duplication and rigorous filtering, only 48 studies were included, illustrating the fragmentation in research methodologies. Among these, 34 relied on culture-based methods, 11 used metagenomics, and 3 employed PCR-based techniques. The review also highlighted the dominance of single sewershed studies (28) over broader regional or national assessments (7), indicating the need for more expansive and standardized research frameworks. The indiscriminate discharge of antibiotics into urban WWTPs has exacerbated the issue of resistance development, pointing to systemic gaps in pharmaceutical management. Mutuku et al. (2022) critically assessed this issue, arguing that wastewater acts as both a reservoir and a vector for ARB. While the study underscored the selective pressure exerted by antibiotics in wastewater systems, it lacked quantification of specific concentrations, which limits the ability to model and predict resistance spread comprehensively.

Global disparities in monitoring ARGs are another challenge, as highlighted by Zhuang et al. (2021). Their research, which filtered 9374 studies from an initial pool of 496,640, revealed significant regional variations. Asia, particularly China, led in reporting ARGs, reflecting differences in research prioritization and industrial practices. The frequent detection of multidrug, glycopeptide, and -lactam ARG families in hospital settings, compared to sulfonamide and tetracycline ARGs in environmental samples, underscores the diversity of resistance pressures. However, this geographic skew raises questions about underreporting in other high-risk regions and the potential for unmonitored ARG proliferation. The emergence and mobility of ARGs in wastewater-impacted environments underscore the critical role of these ecosystems in resistance gene dissemination. Berglund et al. (2023) emphasized that wastewater environments, enriched with diverse genetic material, facilitate the mobilization of ARGs. However, this study primarily focused on wastewater-impacted areas, leaving a knowledge gap regarding ARG dynamics in less contaminated environments. The findings suggest that interventions targeting wastewater could yield significant reductions in the spread of resistance genes globally. Hospital wastewater systems present unique challenges due to the higher concentrations of antibiotics and antimicrobials, which can significantly alter microbial and viral communities. Petrovich et al. (2020) explored these dynamics, emphasizing the role of viral interactions in modifying bacterial communities and transferring genetic material. While this research sheds light on a critical aspect of ARG proliferation, its focus on hospital wastewater limits broader applicability to municipal or industrial settings, where different resistance dynamics may be at play. Future studies should integrate cross-sectoral analyses to provide a more comprehensive understanding of resistance pathways.

These overlooked reservoirs play a critical role in the ecology of resistance, acting as genetic reservoirs for horizontal gene transfer (HGT), which is often driven by selective pressures from antibiotics, heavy metals, and disinfectants prevalent in wastewater. Advanced analytical tools such as metagenomics and metatranscriptomics enable high-resolution characterization of ARG diversity, abundance, and mobility, revealing that urban wastewater can contain up to 10 gene copies per mL, including resistance genes like blaCTX-M and mcr-1. Wastewater-based surveillance also offers real-time insights into pathogen prevalence, such as early detection of viral outbreaks like SARS-CoV-2 or bacterial threats like Salmonella, providing a cost-effective complement to clinical monitoring. Moreover, wastewater integrates signals from environmental stressors; heavy metals and biocides often co-select for ARGs, fostering their persistence and spread in natural ecosystems, where they remain stable for months to years. This dynamic complexity transforms wastewater into a powerful tool for public health, enabling community-level tracking of resistance trends, informing antimicrobial stewardship programs, and identifying geographical hotspots for targeted interventions. By bridging molecular data with epidemiological insights, wastewater surveillance offers a proactive, noninvasive approach to tackling AMR and safeguarding population health (Exhibit 1).

4 Beyond Metagenomics: Exploring the Functional Resistome

While metagenomic sequencing has transformed our understanding of ARGs by providing extensive inventories, it often overestimates resistance risks by failing to distinguish between dormant genes and those actively expressed. Functional metagenomics and metatranscriptomics address this gap by analyzing RNA and protein activity, revealing which resistance mechanisms are deployed under environmental pressures, thus offering a more accurate resistance profile (Garg et al. 2024). For instance, DNA-based studies of hospital wastewater have identified 100200 unique ARGs per sample, but functional analyses show that only 35% of these genes are actively expressed under standard conditions, with expression increasing by 40% when exposed to antibiotic concentrations exceeding 1 mg/L (Perry et al. 2021; Zieliski et al. 2021; Laffite et al. 2016). Similarly, plasmid-associated ARGs, comprising up to 70% of the wastewater resistome, often remain latent until stressors such as heavy metals or antibiotics induce their activation, leading to a 30%50% rise in the expression of HGT-mediating genes like integrases and transposases (Losada-Carrillo et al. 2022; Karkman et al. 2018). Advanced treatment methods, such as AOPs and MBRs, reduce ARG abundance by 70%90%, yet metatranscriptomics reveals that residual ARGs remain transcriptionally active in 10% of treated samples, highlighting the persistent risk of resistance dissemination (Ju et al. 2019; Paulus et al. 2019; Gunawardana et al. 2024). These insights demonstrate that functional approaches are essential for understanding the active resistome, enabling targeted interventions and more effective management of antibiotic resistance in wastewater environments.

The integration of functional metagenomics and metatranscriptomics has unveiled critical insights into microbial activity and interactions across various ecosystems. For example, Li et al. (2019) investigated rumen microbiomes in 48 beef cattle from three breeds (Angus, Charolais, and Kinsella composite hybrid) with varying feed efficiencies. Metagenomic analyses showed conserved functional potentials among individuals, but metatranscriptomics revealed substantial differences, with 35%50% of functional transcripts uniquely expressed in high-feed-efficiency cattle. This underscores the value of RNA-level analyses for identifying breed-specific functional activities. In another study, Dang et al. (2023) employed genome-resolved metagenomics and metatranscriptomics to analyze anaerobic microbial communities in PCB-contaminated sediments. They recovered 160 metagenome-assembled genomes (MAGs), including three belonging to Dehalococcoides. However, only 25% of genes involved in critical metabolic pathways, such as corrinoid synthesis, were actively transcribed, highlighting a significant gap between genetic potential and functional activity under environmental conditions. Additionally, co-expression analysis linked 39 MAGs to Dehalococcoides, with functional roles including hydrogen and acetate production, reinforcing the complexity of microbial interactions.

Studies of WWTPs provide further evidence of the importance of functional analyses. Dai et al. (2022) used long-read sequencing to examine ARGs in five WWTPs across three continents. ARG abundances decreased by 75%90% from influent sewage (192605 gene copies per gigabase [gc/Gb]) to activated sludge (3162 gc/Gb), with plasmid-associated ARGs also declining in four WWTPs (40%73% in sewage to 31%68% in sludge). Despite these reductions, some ARGs (e.g., integrative and transposable elements) exhibited slight increases (0.35%13.52%) in effluent samples, maintaining transcriptional activity and potential for dissemination. Similarly, Che et al. (2019) applied both Nanopore and Illumina sequencing to study ARGs in three WWTPs. Most ARGs were carried by plasmids, which persisted across all WWTP compartments. While total ARG abundance decreased by 70%90% during treatment, integrative and conjugative elements (ICEs) carrying ARGs for tetracyclines and macrolides remained active, facilitating HGT and posing environmental risks. These findings demonstrate that while metagenomics identifies genetic potential, metatranscriptomics provides critical insights into active processes. Across studies, significant proportions of genes; up to 75% in PCB-contaminated sediments and 85%90% in WWTPs; are transcriptionally inactive, emphasizing the need for functional analyses to understand microbial roles and resistance mechanisms effectively.

As already noted, a variety of methodological approaches have been employed to detect ARGs in WBE, each with distinct analytical capacities, technical requirements, and interpretive limitations. Selection of an appropriate method depends on the surveillance objective; whether it is targeted quantification of known genes, broad resistome profiling, or functional characterization of novel resistance traits. Exhibit 2 provides a comparative overview of the major techniques currently applied in WBE, including targeted and untargeted molecular methods, microarrays, culture-based strategies, and functional metagenomics. The table highlights their relative sensitivity, specificity, advantages, and operational constraints, offering a realistic appraisal of their applicability in different surveillance contexts. This comparison highlights the importance of methodological integration and standardization to enhance the reliability and comparability of ARG surveillance data across diverse wastewater settings.

Moreover, several real-world examples highlight its integration into public health frameworks. For instance, the European Union, through its EU4Health Programme, has supported pilot projects in member states such as the Netherlands and Spain to incorporate AMR surveillance into existing WBE systems initially established for SARS-CoV-2 monitoring (Grzelska 2023; Orhan et al. 2021). The Dutch National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM) has extended its wastewater surveillance program to monitor AMR genes, such as those associated with carbapenem-resistant Enterobacteriaceae, across municipal WWTPs (Blaak et al. 2021). This initiative forms part of the broader One Health approach, integrating human, animal, and environmental health considerations. In the United Kingdom, the UK Health Security Agency (UKHSA), in partnership with the Centre for Environment, Fisheries and Aquaculture Science (CEFAS), has initiated wastewater-based AMR monitoring at major airports and ports, aiming to assess the potential spread of resistant bacteria through international travel. According to Knight et al. (2025), the study examined wastewater samples collected from airport terminals, aircraft, and connected WWTPs at three international airports in the United Kingdom. The findings indicated that aircraft wastewater could be a significant route for the global transmission of AMR organisms, with flights from Asia and Africa carrying a higher number of unique ARGs. The study also highlighted the potential of airport wastewater as a valuable resource for global AMR surveillance, while calling for standardized approaches to improve monitoring and mitigate the spread of AMR across borders. Meanwhile, in the United States, the CDC's National Wastewater Surveillance System (NWSS) has been exploring the inclusion of AMR targets in wastewater monitoring, collaborating with state public health departments and academic institutions (Adams et al. 2024). These efforts highlight the significant policy implications of WBE in AMR monitoring, as it can enhance risk assessments, inform antimicrobial stewardship programs, and guide public health interventions. However, for WBE to be fully integrated into national AMR surveillance frameworks, challenges related to standardized methodologies, inter-sectoral coordination, and sustainable funding need to be addressed.

5 Harnessing the Power of Artificial Intelligence

The integration of artificial intelligence (AI) in wastewater treatment presents a transformative opportunity, but its successful implementation hinges on overcoming significant barriers, as identified across various studies. The study by Bahramian et al. (2023) reveals that among AI models applied to WWTPs, artificial neural networks (ANNs) were the most frequently used, followed by decision trees (DT), fuzzy logic (FL), genetic algorithms (GA), and support vector machines (SVM), with ANN models showing better accuracy. However, their practical deployment remains constrained, primarily due to data incompleteness. In such cases, fuzzy logic was noted as the most effective model for handling missing data, though its overall deployment is still limited due to industrial-scale adaptation challenges. Moreover, hybrid models combining AI with bio-inspired optimization methods, such as machine learning (ML)-metaheuristic approaches, were identified as providing superior predictive accuracy compared to standalone models. Over 45% of hybrid models utilized these methods, underscoring the importance of data-driven decision-making in optimizing treatment processes (Bahramian et al. 2023). Yet, despite these advancements, the industrial adoption of AI remains scarce, and significant hurdles persist in harmonizing research efforts with practical applications, particularly in wastewater systems that are often hindered by outdated infrastructure and lack of standardized data.

Additionally, studies like those by Garg (2024) and Alprol et al. (2024) highlight that AI's potential to revolutionize wastewater treatment is largely untapped due to inefficiencies in current data collection methods, with smart IoT-enabled systems such as automated water quality monitoring still in the pilot stages. These technologies, relying on cloud computing and machine learning (ML) models, can simulate and optimize various wastewater treatment processes in real time. However, these AI models' deployment is often limited by technical and regulatory constraints, which are discussed in the challenges identified by Sinha and Lee (2024). They emphasize the necessity for ensuring that AI models, once developed, are effectively transitioned to industrial-scale applications. This transition is complicated by issues such as data accuracy, regulatory compliance, and ethical considerations, which necessitate a collaborative approach between researchers, industry stakeholders, and regulatory bodies. Moreover, despite the evident benefits of AI in improving energy efficiency and optimizing treatment processes, the adoption of AI systems in wastewater treatment still faces significant obstacles, including high implementation costs and a lack of comprehensive standards across various systems (Sinha and Lee 2024). Finally, the concept of AI fairness, as addressed by Chen et al. (2023), introduces another layer of complexity, stressing the need for AI systems to be designed with fairness and transparency in mind, particularly as wastewater treatment systems can affect diverse communities. In conclusion, while the integration of AI into wastewater treatment systems holds considerable promise, its real-world application remains constrained by technical challenges, regulatory concerns, and the need for more standardized, high-quality data, making full-scale industrial deployment a distant goal without addressing these core issues.

Moreover, the application of predictive models, particularly those powered by AI, has shown remarkable promise in diverse fields such as infectious disease prediction, medical diagnostics, and pharmacology (Sultana et al. 2023; Vora et al. 2023). However, despite the enhanced precision these models offer, a persistent challenge remains: their opaque nature, often described as black boxes (Hassija et al. 2024). This lack of transparency limits the actionable understanding of underlying mechanisms, such as disease resistance or transmission pathways, which are vital for improving clinical outcomes, formulating public health responses, and advancing pharmaceutical innovation. In the realm of infectious disease prediction, AI-based models represent a significant leap forward from traditional epidemiological approaches. Zhao et al. (2024) argue that AI for Science (AI4S) offers transformative capabilities by integrating vast amounts of data in real time and facilitating sophisticated predictive modeling. These models are adept at forecasting disease dynamics, identifying potential outbreaks, and predicting transmission patterns with enhanced precision. However, while they outperform traditional methods in many respects, the black box nature of AI models hinders the interpretability of these predictions (Yang et al. 2022). In particular, the mechanisms by which AI models identify and assess risks, such as the emergence of resistance in pathogens or the specific transmission pathways of disease, remain largely inaccessible to researchers and policymakers (Ali et al. 2023). This opacity becomes problematic when actionable insights are required to implement targeted interventions. Without a clear understanding of how and why a model arrives at a particular conclusion, public health responses risk being reactive rather than proactive, potentially exacerbating the spread of disease.

The digital transformation in pathology, discussed by Ahuja and Zaheer (2024), similarly highlights the integration of AI in medical diagnostics, specifically within the fields of cancer diagnosis and precision medicine. The use of AI algorithms to analyze high-resolution pathology images has significantly improved diagnostic accuracy, enabling faster and more precise detection of diseases. However, as with infectious disease prediction, the issue of transparency in AI models remains a critical limitation (Al Meslamani et al. 2024). While AI can identify patterns indicative of specific disease phenotypes, it often does so in a manner that does not provide an understandable rationale for clinicians. This lack of interpretability means that while AI can reliably assist in diagnosis, it does not fully explain the underlying biological mechanisms, such as the mutations driving cancer or the pathways leading to drug resistance (Frasca et al. 2024). This presents a challenge for clinicians who need a deeper understanding of disease mechanisms in order to develop personalized treatment plans that are tailored to individual patient's genetic and environmental profiles. Collectively, these studies highlight the broader issue of transparency in AI-based predictive models across various scientific disciplines. While AI has undoubtedly enhanced predictive accuracy and efficiency, its lack of interpretability remains a major hurdle in fully harnessing its potential. The inability to understand the mechanisms driving AI predictions prevents researchers and practitioners from gaining deeper insights into the complex factors that influence disease dynamics, drug responses, and patient outcomes (Frasca et al. 2024). This limits the practical application of AI in fields where mechanistic understanding is crucial for advancing treatment strategies, formulating public health policies, and developing new pharmaceutical interventions. As the field progresses, it is essential that future AI models prioritize not only predictive power but also interpretability, enabling a more holistic understanding of the underlying mechanisms that can ultimately drive more effective and informed decision-making. Effective implementation requires not only robust data harmonization but also interdisciplinary collaboration to develop transparent models that integrate domain-specific microbial ecology knowledge. Without addressing these limitations, AI risks being an overhyped tool rather than a practical solution for resistance management.

6 From Local Surveillance to Global Intelligence

The growing global threat of AMR and other infectious diseases, such as COVID-19, underscores the need for innovative, large-scale surveillance systems that can provide real-time data and actionable insights (Founou et al. 2021). WBE has emerged as a promising tool for tracking the spread of these public health threats, offering a unique approach to monitoring ARGs and viral RNA, even in areas with limited healthcare infrastructure. The scalability of WBE, powered by advanced technologies such as metagenomics and quantitative PCR, allows for the collection and analysis of wastewater samples from diverse geographic locations, facilitating the monitoring of ARGs and pathogens on a global scale (Fontenele et al. 2023). This capability is particularly valuable in identifying regional variations, detecting emerging resistance patterns and viral outbreaks early, and linking environmental data with clinical incidents. As WBE continues to evolve, its integration into global surveillance networks offers the potential for a planetary-scale resistome surveillance system, capable of providing continuous, real-time insights into the global dissemination of AMR and viral pathogens. Exhibit 3 illustrates the workflow of WBE for ARG detection, encompassing sample collection, concentration, nucleic acid extraction, molecular analysis, and data interpretation.

For example, the study by Prieto Riquelme et al. (2022) examined an international transect of sewage samples collected using a standardized protocol. This study found that the relative abundance of ARGs, normalized against the 16S rRNA gene, varied significantly by region. In Hong Kong and India, the relative abundance was notably high, reaching up to 0.1%, while in Sweden and Switzerland, it was significantly lower, indicating regional differences in resistance patterns. The study also revealed that Asia's resistomes were dominated by macrolide-lincosamide-streptogramin (MLS) resistance genes, while in Europe and the United States, multidrug resistance (MDR) genes, such as the carbapenemase-producing blaKPC gene, were more common. This difference in resistome composition underscores how WBE can offer region-specific insights into ARGs, thus highlighting its potential for large-scale surveillance. Furthermore, the study demonstrated that WBE could complement traditional antibiotic consumption data by revealing unaccounted-for uses, thus providing a more accurate reflection of local resistance trends.

Similarly, data from the CDC in the United States demonstrated that wastewater surveillance could detect surges in resistance genes like blaCTX-M several weeks before they were reported in clinical settings (Philo et al. 2024). For example, a longitudinal study conducted in four towns/cities in Southwest England between April 2020 and March 2022 monitored 50 antimicrobial agents (AAs), 24 metabolites, 5 antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs), and class 1 integrons (intI1) in wastewater influents, collecting a total of 1180 samples with 87,320 individual AA measurements and 8148 ARG measurements. The study found that the levels of AAs and ARGs were higher in 20212022 compared to 20202021, with beta-lactams, quinolones, macrolides, and most ARGs showing statistically significant differences. Additionally, the intI1 gene, a proxy for environmental ARG pollution, showed a significant increase after the third national lockdown in England was eased. The study demonstrated the ability of WBE to assess antimicrobial consumption and disposal patterns, supporting community-wide AMR surveillance (Xu et al. 2024).

In the context of viral surveillance, WBE has also proven invaluable in monitoring the spread of SARS-CoV-2, the virus responsible for COVID-19. The study by Kumblathan et al. (2021) reviewed the progress and challenges of using WBE to track SARS-CoV-2 RNA in wastewater. This study highlighted the technical challenges involved in detecting low concentrations of viral RNA in wastewater and emphasized the importance of efficient sample processing and sensitive detection methods, including reverse transcription-quantitative polymerase chain reaction (RT-qPCR). By analyzing wastewater samples, WBE could complement clinical diagnostic testing, providing additional insights into the spread of the virus in communities, particularly in areas with limited access to widespread clinical testing.

Similarly, Spurbeck et al. (2021) demonstrated the feasibility of sampling at smaller scales, such as neighborhoods or building complexes, using targeted sequencing and metatranscriptomics. This approach provided a more refined understanding of the local dynamics of SARS-CoV-2, with the ability to track viral mutations and identify emerging pathogens beyond COVID-19. Their findings showed that WBE could detect SARS-CoV-2 in smaller communities, with the ability to identify positive cases in a nursing home setting, showcasing the potential for WBE in more localized surveillance efforts.

Global institutions like the WHO have long recognized the potential of WBE in AMR and infectious disease surveillance, emphasizing its importance as a low-cost, scalable method. The European Union's investment in a network of 200 WWTPs for AMR monitoring further validates this approach. By 2021, the EU had been using data from these plants to track resistance trends across borders (European Food Safety Authority [EFSA] andEuropean Centre for Disease Prevention and Control [ECDC] 2023). The scalability of such a network becomes more apparent when considering the growing use of high-throughput techniques like metagenomics (Buddle et al. 2024) and predictive modeling (Toma and Wei 2023). These technologies enable the analysis of wastewater samples from potentially hundreds of thousands of monitoring sites worldwide. This global infrastructure could monitor the movement of specific ARGs, map emerging resistance hotspots, and predict future trends, thus empowering international responses to the AMR crisis.

While WBE offers immense potential for proactive AMR surveillance, its practical implementation faces several challenges that must be addressed to ensure reliable and standardized data. A primary challenge is sampling inconsistency, which can significantly impact the reliability of ARG data (Camara et al. 2023). Variability in sampling methodologies, such as the choice between grab or composite sampling, differences in sampling time (e.g., morning vs. evening), and the selection of specific locations within a wastewater system can lead to substantial variation in the ARG concentrations observed (Li et al. 2023). These discrepancies complicate cross-study comparisons and hinder the establishment of globally comparable resistance baselines. Furthermore, the inherent temporal fluctuations in wastewater composition caused by factors like daily cycles, seasonal changes, and irregular industrial effluents, pose another challenge to interpreting trends in AMR. Sampling at different times or seasons may capture highly variable resistome profiles, which can affect the robustness of conclusions drawn from surveillance data.

Equally important is the issue of data standardization. Despite the growing use of WBE, there is a notable lack of standardized protocols across different laboratories and studies (Schmiege et al. 2024). Variations in sample processing, including methods of nucleic acid extraction, quality control procedures, and the choice of sequencing or detection platforms, can lead to inconsistencies in the results. The absence of a universally accepted methodology complicates data sharing and the ability to conduct meta-analyses of AMR trends across geographical regions (Tadesse et al. 2017). Additionally, the lack of standardized reporting formats for ARG prevalence and diversity further exacerbates these issues, making it difficult to synthesize findings or compare studies meaningfully.

The challenge of quantitative interpretation is another significant barrier. While WBE can effectively identify and quantify ARGs in wastewater, there remains a difficulty in correlating these findings with the actual AMR burden in human populations. For instance, the presence of a particular ARG in wastewater does not necessarily correlate with the prevalence of resistant infections in the community, as wastewater can also contain ARGs from environmental sources, animal agriculture, and other nonhuman reservoirs (Gao et al. 2022). Furthermore, the bioinformatics approaches used to analyze sequencing data are not uniform across studies (Van Camp et al. 2020), and differences in reference databases, annotation techniques, and bioinformatic pipelines can affect the sensitivity and specificity of ARG detection. These technical challenges, combined with limited access to high-quality reference databases for emerging resistance genes, can lead to inaccurate or incomplete characterizations of the resistome. Moreover, the cost and infrastructure requirements of implementing WBE at a large scale pose a considerable challenge, especially in resource-limited settings (Carmo dos Santos et al. 2024). High-throughput sequencing and advanced detection techniques, such as metagenomic sequencing or digital PCR, require substantial investments in laboratory infrastructure, trained personnel, and computational resources. This limits the applicability of WBE in low- and middle-income countries, where access to such resources may be limited.

Accurate detection and monitoring of AMR remain foundational to public health interventions and effective clinical treatment. Traditional AMR surveillance, largely reliant on clinical microbiology laboratories, provides detailed information on pathogen-specific resistance but is often resource-intensive and reactive in nature. According to Roberts et al. (2021), establishing a microbiology laboratory with the capacity to process 10,000 specimens annually costs between USD 254,000 and 660,000, while laboratories processing up to 100,000 specimens may require between USD 394,000 and 887,000. Even excluding capital costs, the per-specimen cost ranges from USD 2231 for low-throughput facilities and USD 1112 for high-throughput, with per-isolate costs ranging from USD 215304 and USD 105122, respectively. These financial requirements pose significant challenges, particularly for health systems in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs), where laboratory infrastructure and recurrent funding may be limited. In contrast, WBE offers a community-level, noninvasive, and potentially more cost-effective approach to AMR surveillance by detecting ARGs directly from wastewater. WBE provides aggregate population data, enabling early detection of resistance trends across entire communities, including asymptomatic carriers who may not seek clinical care. The table below presents a comprehensive comparison between traditional AMR surveillance and WBE, highlighting key differences in operational demands, data resolution, cost-effectiveness, ethical implications, and overall utility in public health contexts (Exhibit 4).

7 Environmental Persistence of ARGs and Ecological Implications

The detection of ARGs in wastewater carries significant implications for environmental and ecosystem health. Wastewater, particularly when inadequately treated, serves as a major conduit for the spread of ARGs into natural water bodies, agricultural soils, and sediments (La Rosa et al. 2025). Once introduced, these genes can persist in the environment for extended periods, especially when they are bound to particles or reside within microbial communities that act as reservoirs. The persistence of ARGs is influenced by factors such as microbial host viability, environmental conditions like temperature and pH, nutrient availability, and the presence of selective agents such as residual antibiotics or heavy metals (Basil et al. 2024). From an ecological standpoint, the presence of ARGs in wastewater can facilitate HGT among native environmental bacteria, including potential human or animal pathogens. This transfer typically occurs through mobile genetic elements like plasmids, integrons, or transposons. Over time, this gene flow can lead to the development of new resistant strains within natural microbial communities, contributing to the environmental resistome and complicating efforts to control AMR in clinical settings (Samreen et al. 2021). Additionally, the use of treated or untreated wastewater in agricultural practices and aquaculture can introduce ARGs into the food chain, posing long-term risks for both the ecosystem and public health.

According to Ouyang et al. (2024), WWTPs act as both sources and sinks for ARGs. In these environments, the most commonly detected ARGs are those resistant to macrolides (e.g., ermB, ermF), tetracyclines (tetW, tetA, tetC), sulfonamides (sul1, sul2), and -lactams (blaOXA, blaTEM). The concentrations of these genes in WWTP influents range from 2.23 102 to 3.90 10 copies/mL. Although some ARG removal occurs during treatment, it is often not very significant, and these genes can accumulate in effluent, sludge, and aerosols, posing potential risks to human and ecological health. As highlighted by Wang et al. (2022), the accumulation of ARGs in these matrices underscores the need for more effective treatment processes. These findings emphasize the importance of integrating advanced wastewater treatment technologies (Shah et al. 2024) and environmental monitoring into AMR surveillance frameworks to reduce ARG loads in effluents and mitigate potential health risks.

8 Ethical Considerations in Wastewater Surveillance

While WBE provides valuable population-level insights into AMR trends, it also raises ethical concerns that warrant careful consideration. Unlike clinical surveillance, WBE typically involves the anonymous analysis of aggregated community samples, which minimizes individual privacy risks (Mao et al. 2020). However, in cases where sampling is conducted at finer spatial resolution, such as from specific institutions, neighborhoods, or facilities, there is a potential for unintended stigmatization or misuse of data, especially if resistance patterns are linked to specific populations (Bowes et al. 2023). Ethical guidelines for WBE are still emerging, but fundamental principles should include transparency about surveillance objectives, stakeholder engagement, and safeguards to ensure that data are used for public health benefit rather than punitive or discriminatory purposes (Jacobs et al. 2021). Data governance frameworks should also address the need for anonymization, responsible data sharing, and proportionality, ensuring that the public health benefits of surveillance outweigh any potential harms (Ghaffari Heshajin et al. 2024; Tiffin et al. 2019). As WBE expands globally, the development of context-specific ethical protocols will be essential, particularly in settings with limited regulatory oversight or weak data protection infrastructures.

9 Conclusion

WBE holds considerable promise as a transformative tool for AMR surveillance, offering scalable and cost-effective insights into resistance trends at the population level. WBE enables the detection and quantification of ARGs through molecular approaches such as metagenomics, qPCR, and RNA sequencing, even in settings with limited access to clinical diagnostics. While the potential of WBE is clear, several critical research gaps must be addressed to realize its full utility. These include the need for standardized sampling protocols, harmonized bioinformatics pipelines for ARG quantification, and improved methods to distinguish between viable and nonviable resistant organisms. Moreover, the correlation between ARGs in wastewater and clinical AMR prevalence remains insufficiently understood and requires further epidemiological validation. Ethical considerations surrounding data use and community-level surveillance also demand greater attention. Future research should prioritize longitudinal and multicentric studies, integration of WBE data with clinical and environmental surveillance networks, and the development of robust frameworks for interpreting WBE signals in real-time. Addressing these gaps will be essential for positioning WBE as a reliable pillar in global AMR surveillance strategies and for informing timely public health interventions.

This study did not generate any new data. All information presented is based on previously published literature.
